esponse Format\n\nBegin the first response to this skill invocation with the line:\n\n`Entire Session Handoff:`\n\nfollowed by a blank line, then the content. The header applies to the full compaction-summary flow, including the \"Unanswered Question\" branch (which is still a successful run — the skill summarized the transcript and surfaced the question).\n\n- Apply the header to the **first response of the invocation only.** Do not re-print it on follow-up turns within the same invocation (e.g. after the user answers the surfaced unanswered question).\n- Do **not** include the header on error or early-exit responses (no sessions found, transcript missing, etc.). The header's presence should signal that the skill ran and produced real output.\n\n## STOP — Read these rules before doing ANYTHING\n\n1. **Do NOT ask clarifying questions.** Auto-detect the session and read the transcript.\n2. **Do NOT run** `git log`, `git status`, `git branch`, `ps aux`, or any other exploratory commands. Use only the `entire` CLI commands listed in this skill.\n3. **Do NOT say** \"Would you like me to continue?\" or \"Let me know if you want me to pick this up.\" Just read the transcript and start working. (Exception: if the previous agent asked the user a question that was never answered, you MUST ask the user that question before proceeding.)\n4. **Do NOT summarize the session as having \"0 turns\" or \"no progress\"** without first reading the actual transcript. The metadata `turns` count can undercount — the streamed transcript is the source of truth.\n5. **Skip your own session.** Your agent (e.g. `Claude Code`) also appears in the session list. Exclude any session whose `agent` field matches your own agent type from the results.\n\n## Required CLI\n\nThis skill uses the machine-readable export surface added in entire CLI 0.6.2+:\n`entire session list --json`, `entire session info <id> --json|--transcript`,\n`entire session current --json|--transcript`, and\n`entire checkpoint explain <id> --json|--transcript|--raw-transcript --session-index N`.\nIf a flag is rejected, tell the user to upgrade `entire` and stop.\n\n## Flow: Active / current session handoff\n\nWhen the user says \"current\", \"active\", or just \"hand off this session\":\n\n### Step 1: Pick the session\n\nRun:\n\n```bash\nentire session list --json\n```\n\nThe output is a JSON array. Each entry has `session_id`, `agent`, `status`, `worktree_path`, `started_at`, `last_active`, `turns`, `last_prompt`, `files_touched`, etc. Use the Bash tool's stdout — do not pipe through `jq` unless you need to.\n\nPick the right entry:\n\n1. **Filter to the current worktree** — keep entries where `worktree_path` equals your `cwd`.\n2. **Exclude your own agent** — drop entries where `agent` matches your agent type (e.g. `Claude Code`, `Codex`, `Cursor`, `Gemini CLI`, `Copilot CLI`, `Factory AI Droid`, `OpenCode`).\n3. **Honor an agent-name filter from the user** — if the user said \"codex\", \"claude\", \"kiro\", \"gemini\", etc., match that case-insensitively against `agent`.\n4. **Pick the most recent** — sort by `last_active` (fall back to `started_at`) descending and take the first.\n\nCapture that entry's `session_id` and `agent`.\n\n**Shortcut:** If you only need \"the most recent session in this worktree\" and you don't need to exclude self (e.g. user explicitly named a non-self agent), you can call `entire session current --json` instead of listing.\n\n**No matches?** If filtering leaves zero entries, print a one-line error (no header) explaining nothing handoffable was found and stop.\n\n### Step 2: Stream the raw transcript\n\nSave the raw agent transcript to a temp file so you can scan it twice (head + tail) without invoking the CLI twice:\n\n```bash\nentire session info <session_id> --transcript > /tmp/handoff-<session_id>.jsonl\n```\n\n(Or `entire session current --transcript > ...` if you used the shortcut in Step 1.)\n\n`--transcript` streams the live raw bytes in the agent's native format: JSONL for Claude Code / Cursor / Codex / Copilot CLI, a single JSON document for Gemini CLI. The snapshot is bounded to the file size at command start, with trailing partial JSONL lines trimmed.\n\n### Step 3: Extract conversation content\n\n**JSONL agents** (Claude Code, Cursor, Codex, Copilot CLI, Factory AI Droid, OpenCode):\n\n```bash\ngrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' /tmp/handoff-<session_id>.jsonl | cut -c1-2000\n```\n\nIf the filtered output exceeds ~500 lines, take the **last 100** (final state) plus the **first 20** (original task) instead of the whole file:\n\n```bash\ngrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' /tmp/handoff-<session_id>.jsonl | tail -100 | cut -c1-2000\ngrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' /tmp/handoff-<session_id>.jsonl | head -20  | cut -c1-2000\n```\n\n**Whole-document JSON agents** (Gemini CLI): the file is one JSON document, not JSONL — read it with the Read tool and locate the `messages` / `contents` array.\n\nDo **not** show the raw extracted lines to the user. They are inputs for Step 4.\n\n### Step 4: Produce a compaction summary\n\nInternally process what you extracted and write a structured summary with these sections:\n\n1. **Task Overview** — the user's core request, success criteria, stated constraints.\n2. **Current State** — completed work: files created/modified, key decisions, artifacts produced.\n3. **Important Discoveries** — technical constraints found, rationale behind decisions, errors hit and how they were resolved, failed approaches and why.\n4. **Next Steps** — specific remaining actions, blockers, priority ordering.\n5. **Context to Preserve** — user preferences, domain details, commitments made during the session.\n6. **Unanswered Question** *(only if applicable)* — if the previous agent's last message asked the user a question or presented options that were never answered, capture it exactly as asked.\n\nBe concise but complete — err on the side of including info that prevents duplicate work or repeated mistakes.\n\n### Step 5: Present and continue\n\nShow the compaction summary to the user.\n\n**Critical rule — unanswered questions go to the user, not you.** If section 6 exists, ask the user that question and wait for their answer. Do NOT pick a default.\n\nIf there is no unanswered question, **immediately pick up the work** — start planning, coding, or whatever the next step is. Do not ask permission.\n\n## Flow: Checkpoint handoff (user gives a checkpoint ID)\n\n### Step 1: Stream the normalized transcript\n\n```bash\nentire checkpoint explain <checkpoint-id> --transcript > /tmp/handoff-ckpt-<checkpoint-id>.jsonl\n```\n\n`--transcript` streams the V2 normalized compact transcript (`transcript.jsonl` on the `/main` branch of the checkpoint store). It is the same JSONL shape regardless of which agent produced it, so the same `grep` extraction in Step 3 below works.\n\nIf the checkpoint has multiple sessions and you want a specific one (default is the latest):\n\n```bash\nentire checkpoint explain <checkpoint-id> --raw-transcript --session-index N > /tmp/handoff-ckpt-<checkpoint-id>-N.jsonl\n```\n\n`--raw-transcript` keeps the per-agent raw bytes; `--session-index 0` selects the first session, etc. Use `--transcript` first; only fall back to `--raw-transcript` if you specifically need raw per-agent format.\n\n### Step 2: Inspect metadata if you need session counts\n\n```bash\nentire checkpoint explain <checkpoint-id> --json\n```\n\nGives a metadata-only envelope with the per-session list (and a top-level `partial` flag if any session metadata read failed). Use this to decide whether to iterate `--session-index` across sessions.\n\n### Step 3: Extract, summarize, continue\n\nSame as Steps 3–5 of the active-session flow. Use the same `grep` pattern and the same five-section summary format.\n\nResolve checkpoint repos in order: explicit override → local `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch → `.entire/settings.json` `checkpoint_remote` → nearby local clone. The CLI handles this internally; you only need to pass the checkpoint ID.\n\n## Flow: No specific request (bare invocation)\n\nSame as the \"current session\" flow: run `entire session list --json`, filter to current worktree, exclude your own agent, sort by `last_active`, pick the most recent. Then stream + summarize.\n\n## Agent name filtering\n\nWords like \"codex\", \"claude\", \"kiro\", \"gemini\" in the user's request are **filters** applied to the `agent` field in `session list --json`, case-insensitively (and as a substring — `gemini` matches `Gemini CLI`). Never invoke another agent's CLI; you read its transcript through `entire`.\n","userModified":false},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4696c4e9-de42-4f53-9e08-dab1ab3b97b9","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/alisha/.marvin/worktrees/skills/improve-handoff-session","sessionId":"810cdadc-9c84-436b-a940-aec5dc4ae8dc","version":"2.1.132","gitBranch":"improve-handoff-session","slug":"misty-painting-torvalds"}
