{"parentUuid":"8ab4d879-59e5-40b5-88ac-695a94db67f0","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"83db36fc-6cdc-4968-8271-4762d1758cf3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EmNtuaX815cyzF3tsj2UGL","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: session-handoff\n3\tdescription: Use when the user wants to continue work from one agent in another agent, inspect recent sessions, or summarize a saved session or checkpoint for handoff\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\t# Hand-Off Session\n7\t\n8\t## Response Format\n9\t\n10\tBegin the first response to this skill invocation with the line:\n11\t\n12\t`Entire Session Handoff:`\n13\t\n14\tfollowed by a blank line, then the content. Apply the header to the **first response of the invocation only** — not on follow-up turns and not on error / early-exit responses (no sessions found, transcript missing). Its presence signals the skill ran and produced real output. The \"Unanswered Question\" branch still gets the header.\n15\t\n16\t## STOP — Read these rules before doing ANYTHING\n17\t\n18\t1. **Do NOT ask clarifying questions.** Auto-detect the session and read the transcript.\n19\t2. **Do NOT run** `git log`, `git status`, `git branch`, `ps aux`, or any other exploratory commands. Use only the `entire` CLI commands listed below.\n20\t3. **Do NOT say** \"Would you like me to continue?\" or \"Let me know if you want me to pick this up.\" Just read the transcript and start working. Exception: if the previous agent asked the user a question that was never answered, you MUST ask the user that question before proceeding.\n21\t\n22\tRequired CLI: entire 0.6.2+ (`session list --json`, `session info --transcript`, `session current --json|--transcript`, `checkpoint explain --json|--transcript|--raw-transcript --session-index N`). If a flag is rejected, tell the user to upgrade and stop.\n23\t\n24\t## Flow: Active session handoff (default — also covers bare invocation and \"current\"/\"active\")\n25\t\n26\t### Step 1: Pick the session\n27\t\n28\tRun:\n29\t\n30\t```bash\n31\tentire session list --json\n32\t```\n33\t\n34\tEach entry has `session_id`, `agent`, `status`, `worktree_path`, `started_at`, `last_active`, `turns`, `last_prompt`, `files_touched`. From that array:\n35\t\n36\t1. Scope to this worktree. `worktree_path` is the worktree root; your `cwd` may be a subdirectory of it. Keep an entry if `cwd` starts with `worktree_path` **or** `worktree_path` starts with `cwd` (treats both as paths). If that filter yields zero entries, fall back to the unscoped list rather than failing — better to summarize a slightly-off session than to refuse the handoff.\n37\t2. Drop entries where `agent` matches the agent currently running this skill (e.g. `Claude Code`, `Codex`, `Cursor`, `Gemini CLI`, `Copilot CLI`, `Factory AI Droid`, `OpenCode`).\n38\t3. If the user named an agent (\"codex\", \"claude\", \"kiro\", \"gemini\", …), keep only entries whose `agent` matches case-insensitively as a substring (so `gemini` matches `Gemini CLI`).\n39\t4. Sort by `last_active` (fall back to `started_at`) descending; take the first.\n40\t\n41\tIf even the unscoped list is empty after self/agent-name filtering, print a one-line error (no header) and stop.\n42\t\n43\t### Step 2: Stream the raw transcript\n44\t\n45\t```bash\n46\tentire session info <session_id> --transcript > /tmp/handoff-<session_id>.jsonl\n47\t```\n48\t\n49\tSnapshot is bounded to the file size at command start. Output is JSONL for most agents and a single JSON document for Gemini CLI.\n50\t\n51\t### Step 3: Extract conversation content\n52\t\n53\tFor Gemini CLI (whole-document JSON), read `/tmp/handoff-<session_id>.jsonl` with the Read tool and locate the messages / contents array. For everyone else:\n54\t\n55\t```bash\n56\tgrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' /tmp/handoff-<session_id>.jsonl | cut -c1-2000 | head -20    # original task\n57\tgrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' /tmp/handoff-<session_id>.jsonl | cut -c1-2000 | tail -100   # final state\n58\t```\n59\t\n60\tDo not show the raw lines to the user. They are inputs for Step 4.\n61\t\n62\t### Step 4: Produce a compaction summary\n63\t\n64\tWrite a structured summary with these sections:\n65\t\n66\t1. **Task Overview** — the user's core request, success criteria, stated constraints.\n67\t2. **Current State** — completed work: files created/modified, key decisions, artifacts produced.\n68\t3. **Important Discoveries** — technical constraints found, rationale behind decisions, errors hit and how they were resolved, failed approaches and why.\n69\t4. **Next Steps** — specific remaining actions, blockers, priority ordering.\n70\t5. **Context to Preserve** — user preferences, domain details, commitments made during the session.\n71\t6. **Unanswered Question** *(only if applicable)* — if the previous agent's last message asked the user a question or presented options that were never answered, capture it exactly as asked.\n72\t\n73\tBe concise but complete — err on the side of including info that prevents duplicate work or repeated mistakes.\n74\t\n75\t### Step 5: Present and continue\n76\t\n77\tShow the compaction summary.\n78\t\n79\t**Critical rule — unanswered questions go to the user, not you.** If section 6 exists, ask the user that question and wait for their answer. Do NOT pick a default.\n80\t\n81\tOtherwise, **immediately pick up the work** — start planning, coding, or whatever the next step is. Do not ask permission.\n82\t\n83\t## Flow: Checkpoint handoff (user gives a checkpoint ID)\n84\t\n85\t### Step 1: Enumerate sessions\n86\t\n87\t```bash\n88\tentire checkpoint explain <checkpoint-id> --json\n89\t```\n90\t\n91\tThe envelope's `sessions` array tells you how many sessions contributed to this checkpoint. Multi-session checkpoints are common (parallel agents, retries, multi-phase work) and earlier sessions often carry the rationale, failed approaches, and user constraints that the latest session takes for granted. **Do not skip them.**\n92\t\n93\t### Step 2: Stream every session's transcript\n94\t\n95\tIf the checkpoint has exactly one session, stream the normalized compact transcript:\n96\t\n97\t```bash\n98\tentire checkpoint explain <checkpoint-id> --transcript > /tmp/handoff-ckpt-<checkpoint-id>.jsonl\n99\t```\n100\t\n101\tIf it has more than one (`sessions.length > 1`), iterate over every index — do **not** rely on the `--transcript` default (latest session only):\n102\t\n103\t```bash\n104\t# for N in 0 .. sessions.length-1\n105\tentire checkpoint explain <checkpoint-id> --raw-transcript --session-index <N> > /tmp/handoff-ckpt-<checkpoint-id>-<N>.jsonl\n106\t```\n107\t\n108\t`--raw-transcript` keeps the per-agent raw bytes so the same JSONL grep extraction works. Index 0 is the first session.\n109\t\n110\t### Step 3: Extract, summarize, continue\n111\t\n112\tRun the Step 3 grep extraction (head + tail) from the active-session flow on each `/tmp/handoff-ckpt-*.jsonl` file, then merge the results into a single five-section summary. Treat earlier sessions as the source of \"Important Discoveries\" and \"Context to Preserve\"; the latest session is the source of \"Current State\" and \"Next Steps\". Then continue per Step 5 of the active-session flow.\n113\t"}]},"uuid":"19317f37-c6ec-4ee2-8881-60c85ba9d7b6","timestamp":"2026-05-08T20:13:21.056Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/alisha/.marvin/worktrees/skills/improve-handoff-session/skills/session-handoff/SKILL.md","content":"---\nname: session-handoff\ndescription: Use when the user wants to continue work from one agent in another agent, inspect recent sessions, or summarize a saved session or checkpoint for handoff\n---\n\n# Hand-Off Session\n\n## Response Format\n\nBegin the first response to this skill invocation with the line:\n\n`Entire Session Handoff:`\n\nfollowed by a blank line, then the content. Apply the header to the **first response of the invocation only** — not on follow